		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Speed of light</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">"Lightspeed" redirects here. For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Lightspeed_(disambiguation)" title="Lightspeed (disambiguation)">Lightspeed (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div class="dablink">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Speed_of_light_(disambiguation)" title="Speed of light (disambiguation)">Speed of light (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div class="dablink">For aspects of light other than its speed, see specific topics: for example, for light from the sun , see <a href="/wiki/Sunlight" title="Sunlight">Sunlight</a> and <a href="/wiki/Solar_variation" title="Solar variation">Solar variation</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:266px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Lasertests.jpg" class="image" title="Here, laser light in air is traveling at 99.97% the speed of light in a vacuum.[1]"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Lasertests.jpg/264px-Lasertests.jpg" width="264" height="326" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Lasertests.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Here, <a href="/wiki/Laser" title="Laser">laser</a> light in air is traveling at 99.97% the speed of light in a vacuum.<sup id="cite_ref-Podesta_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Podesta-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Deuterium-tritium_fusion.svg" class="image" title="Fusion of deuterium with tritium creating helium-4, freeing a neutron, and releasing 17.59 MeV of energy by conversion of mass in accord with E=mc2.[2]"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Deuterium-tritium_fusion.svg/180px-Deuterium-tritium_fusion.svg.png" width="180" height="208" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Deuterium-tritium_fusion.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Fusion of <a href="/wiki/Deuterium" title="Deuterium">deuterium</a> with <a href="/wiki/Tritium" title="Tritium">tritium</a> creating <a href="/wiki/Helium-4" title="Helium-4">helium-4</a>, freeing a <a href="/wiki/Neutron" title="Neutron">neutron</a>, and releasing 17.59 <a href="/wiki/Electronvolt" title="Electronvolt" class="mw-redirect">MeV</a> of energy by conversion of mass in accord with <i>E=mc<sup>2</sup></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-Shultis_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Shultis-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>speed of light</b> in <a href="/wiki/Free_space" title="Free space">free space</a> is a <a href="/wiki/Physical_constant" title="Physical constant">physical constant</a> defined as 299,792,458 <a href="/wiki/Metres_per_second" title="Metres per second" class="mw-redirect">metres per second</a>. It is often denoted by the symbol <i>c</i> - originating from the Latin word <i>celeritās</i> (<a href="/wiki/Speed" title="Speed">speed</a>). The speed of light was officially included in the <a href="/wiki/International_System_of_Units" title="International System of Units">International System of Units</a> on October 21, <a href="/wiki/1983" title="1983">1983</a>, leaving the <a href="/wiki/Metre" title="Metre">metre</a> defined in terms of both <i>c</i> and the <a href="/wiki/Second" title="Second">second</a>.</p>
<p>When light is traveling in a medium, its speed is less than <i>c</i> and becomes a function of the <a href="/wiki/Refractive_index" title="Refractive index">refractive index</a> of the material.</p>
