<li id="cite_note-Effective-32"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Effective_32-0" title="">^</a></b> General relativity predicts distortion of space by gravity that can be expressed as a effective refractive index. The speed of light approaches its speed in ideal vacuum only for zero gravitation. See <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFKK_Nandi_.27.27et_al..27.272003">KK Nandi <i>et al.</i> (2003). "<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/gr-qc/0208035v1" class="external text" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/gr-qc/0208035v1" rel="nofollow">An analog of the Fizeau effect in an effective optical medium</a>". <i>Phys Rev D</i> <b>67</b><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/gr-qc/0208035v1" class="external free" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/gr-qc/0208035v1" rel="nofollow">http://arxiv.org/abs/gr-qc/0208035v1</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=An+analog+of+the+Fizeau+effect+in+an+effective+optical+medium&amp;rft.jtitle=Phys+Rev+D&amp;rft.aulast=KK+Nandi+%27%27et+al.%27%27&amp;rft.au=KK+Nandi+%27%27et+al.%27%27&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.volume=67&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farxiv.org%2Fabs%2Fgr-qc%2F0208035v1&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Speed_of_light"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span>, <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFHenry_Lipson_.26_DS_Tannhauser1995">Henry Lipson &amp; DS Tannhauser (1995). <i><a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=f1URQJf7ZzgC&amp;pg=PA33" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=f1URQJf7ZzgC&amp;pg=PA33" rel="nofollow">Optical Physics</a></i>. Cambridge University Press. p.&#160;33. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0521436311" class="internal">ISBN 0521436311</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=f1URQJf7ZzgC&amp;pg=PA33" class="external free" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=f1URQJf7ZzgC&amp;pg=PA33" rel="nofollow">http://books.google.com/books?id=f1URQJf7ZzgC&amp;pg=PA33</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Optical+Physics&amp;rft.aulast=Henry+Lipson+%26+DS+Tannhauser&amp;rft.au=Henry+Lipson+%26+DS+Tannhauser&amp;rft.date=1995&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B33&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=0521436311&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Df1URQJf7ZzgC%26pg%3DPA33&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Speed_of_light"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> and <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFHE_Puthoff2002">HE Puthoff (2002). <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=_6g0qufw9oAC&amp;pg=PA431" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=_6g0qufw9oAC&amp;pg=PA431" rel="nofollow">"Polarizable vacuum approach to general relativity"</a>. in RL Amaroso <i>et al.</i>. <i>Gravitation and Cosmology</i>. Springer. p.&#160;431. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1402008856" class="internal">ISBN 1402008856</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=_6g0qufw9oAC&amp;pg=PA431" class="external free" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=_6g0qufw9oAC&amp;pg=PA431" rel="nofollow">http://books.google.com/books?id=_6g0qufw9oAC&amp;pg=PA431</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Polarizable+vacuum+approach+to+general+relativity&amp;rft.atitle=Gravitation+and+Cosmology&amp;rft.aulast=HE+Puthoff&amp;rft.au=HE+Puthoff&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B431&amp;rft.pub=Springer&amp;rft.isbn=1402008856&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D_6g0qufw9oAC%26pg%3DPA431&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Speed_of_light"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span>. A summary of recent work is found in <cite style="font-style:norma